://localhost/daryl-james/?post_type=readersdiscussions&#038;p=101',0,'readersdiscussions','',0),(102,1,'2018-07-10 05:42:49','2018-07-10 05:42:49','Daryl L. James, Jr.s story is a history like none weve heard before. We learn in his book, <em>A Gay Mans Odyssey Through the 20th Century and Beyond,</em> what it was like to be a gay man in the Depression in Middle America, when he was outed in his junior year of high school and faced the terror of being set-up and arrested by the vice-squad in LA or being preyed upon by violent homophobes in Chicago. He is a proud veteran of both WWII and the Korean War, where he served as a radio man doing top-secret work in places like the Amazon and the island of Guam. He built his career in publishing and advertising, and worked on Madison Avenue and Hollywood. He survived both McCartheyism and the AIDS epidemic, suffering great loss as a result of each. His stories and the stories of the men and women he has loved strike a huge chord in our society today. Like Forrest Gump, Daryl has been on the ground and present, recording the details of many of our most amazing historic times and events.','Book','','inherit','closed','closed','','11-autosave-v1','','','2018-07-10 05:42:49','2018-07-10 05:42:49','',11,'http://localhost/daryl-james/11-autosave-v1',0,'revision','',0),(104,1,'2018-07-10 05:42:58','2018-07-10 05:42:58','Daryl L. James, Jr.s story is a history like none weve heard before. We learn in his book, <em>A Gay Mans Odyssey Through the 20th Century and Beyond,</em> what it was like to be a gay man in the Depression in Middle America, when he was outed in his junior year of high school and faced the terror of being set-up and arrested by the vice-squad in LA or being preyed upon by violent homophobes in Chicago. He is a proud veteran of both WWII and the Korean War, where he served as a radio man doing top-secret work in places like the Amazon and the island of Guam. He built his career in publishing and advertising, and worked on Madison Avenue and Hollywood. He survived both McCartheyism and the AIDS epidemic, suffering great loss as a result of each. His stories and the stories of the men and women he has loved strike a huge chord in our society today. Like Forrest Gump, Daryl has been on the ground and present, recording the details of many of our most amazing historic times and events.','Book','','inherit','closed','closed','','11-revision-v1','','','2018-07-10 05:42:58','2018-07-10 05:42:58','',11,'http://localhost/daryl-james/11-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(106,1,'2018-07-10 05:43:28','2018-07-10 05:43:28','It is Daryl L. James, Jr.s love for the written word that constantly encourages him to write. At 92, he has experienced the countrys great struggles and great triumphs. He survived the Great Depression, and he joined the US Navy during World War II and Korean War. After being discharged, he pursued a career in magazine publishing.','Author','','inherit','closed','closed','','13-revision-v1','','','2018-07-10 05:43:28','2018-07-10 05:43:28','',13,'http://localhost/daryl-james/13-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(108,1,'2018-07-10 05:44:41','2018-07-10 05:44:41','It was during this visit that my eyes fell upon the most beautiful piece of mens clothing that screamed for my attention and purchase. It was elegant. It was billowy, and without a doubt, the most beguiling yellow shirt I had ever seen. I luxuriated in the elegant opulence of its seductive silkiness that scintillated every fiber of my upper body. I knew that this shirt was me. I would wear it proudly, perhaps subconsciously flaunting my true identity to the rampant homophobia of those times. One caveat temporarily quashed the sale. My dear daddy recognized the not-so-subtle implications of this purchase.\n\nI feel compelled to break a self-imposed silence on my recall of Rock Hudsons marriage to Phyllis Gates in the mid-fifties of the last century. Meeting Phyllis in 1953, at the notorious Tropical Village gay bar and beach in Venice, California, we immediately established a close bond. First of all, she was a gorgeous woman, very feminine, untypical of the lesbian image of that era. She was having problems with a girl friend working in Las Vegas, and I related, since I too was having similar problems with my sailor boyfriend serving on a cruiser in the Korean War.\n\nDecember 31, 1999, the last hours of the last day of the year, decade, century, and millennium; with these final moments ebbing away. I feel a need to experience every precious second. For me to leave behind the 20th Century is traumatic. An era is quickly moving into the history books, and I am not sure I am ready to say good-bye to a period of time that covers so much of my life. Arriving on the planet back in 1926, it has been my privilege to observe 74 percent of the century.\n','Excerpts','','inherit','closed','closed','','15-autosave-v1','','','2018-07-10 05:44:41','2018-07-10 05:44:41','',15,'http://localhost/daryl-james/15-autosave-v1',0,'revision','',0),(110,1,'2018-07-10 05:48:01','2018-07-10 05:48:01','It was during this visit that my eyes fell upon the most beautiful piece of mens clothing that screamed for my attention and purchase. It was elegant. It was billowy, and without a doubt, the most beguiling yellow shirt I had ever seen. I luxuriated in the elegant opulence of its seductive silkiness that scintillated every fiber of my upper body. I knew that this shirt was me. I would wear it proudly, perhaps subconsciously flaunting my true identity to the rampant homophobia of those times. One caveat temporarily quashed the sale. My dear daddy recognized the not-so-subtle implications of this purchase.\r\n\r\nI feel compelled to break a self-imposed silence on my recall of Rock Hudsons marriage to Phyllis Gates in the mid-fifties of the last century. Meeting Phyllis in 1953, at the notorious Tropical Village gay bar and beach in Venice, California, we immediately established a close bond. First of all,